Nice—this is actually one of the most practical patterns (undo/redo, versioning, rollback). I’ll compress everything into a super-clear mental model + interview-ready explanation.

🧠 1️⃣ What Memento REALLY is

👉 One-line definition:

Memento pattern stores object state snapshots so you can restore (undo) later
🎯 Core Use Case
UNDO / REDO functionality

Examples:

Text editor undo

Config rollback

Game save/load

Transaction rollback

🧩 2️⃣ 3 Components (Must Remember)
🟢 1. Originator (Main Object)
The object whose state we want to save

Example:

Configuration
Editor
GameState
🟡 2. Memento (Snapshot)
Stores state of Originator

👉 Immutable snapshot

🔵 3. Caretaker (History Manager)
Stores list of mementos
Handles undo/redo
🔥 3️⃣ Visual Flow (VERY IMPORTANT)
Originator → createMemento() → Memento → Caretaker stores

Caretaker → undo() → returns Memento → Originator restores
⚡ 4️⃣ Your Example (Simplified)
Step 1: Originator
class Configuration {
    int height;
    int width;

    Memento createMemento() {
        return new Memento(height, width);
    }

    void restore(Memento m) {
        this.height = m.height;
        this.width = m.width;
    }
}
Step 2: Memento
class Memento {
    int height;
    int width;

    Memento(int h, int w) {
        this.height = h;
        this.width = w;
    }
}
Step 3: Caretaker
class Caretaker {
    Stack<Memento> history = new Stack<>();

    void save(Memento m) {
        history.push(m);
    }

    Memento undo() {
        return history.pop();
    }
}
Step 4: Client Flow
Configuration config = new Configuration();
Caretaker caretaker = new Caretaker();

// State 1
config.height = 5;
config.width = 10;
caretaker.save(config.createMemento());

// State 2
config.height = 7;
config.width = 12;
caretaker.save(config.createMemento());

// State 3
config.height = 9;
config.width = 14;

// UNDO
config.restore(caretaker.undo());
🧠 5️⃣ KEY Insight (Interview Gold)
❗ Why not store object directly?
Encapsulation break ❌
✅ Memento solves this
Originator decides:
- what to save
- what to restore

👉 External world doesn't see internal details

🔥 6️⃣ Why It’s Powerful
✅ Encapsulation safe
No direct access to object internals
✅ Easy undo/redo
Just push/pop snapshots
✅ Flexible
Can store partial state or full state
❌ 7️⃣ Drawbacks
❌ Memory heavy
Many snapshots → high memory usage
❌ Performance
Deep copy cost (big objects)
🧠 8️⃣ When to Use (Important)

Use Memento when:

✔ Need undo/redo
✔ Need rollback
✔ Need version history
✔ Want encapsulation safe state saving
⚡ 9️⃣ Interview Triggers

If interviewer says:

“Design undo functionality”
“Save previous states”
“Rollback system”
“Version history”

👉 Your brain:

MEMENTO PATTERN ⚡
🆚 10️⃣ Memento vs Command (Common Confusion)
Memento
Stores STATE
Command
Stores ACTION
Example:
Pattern	Stores
Memento	height=5, width=10
Command	"turn AC ON"

👉 Combine both → powerful undo system

🧠 11️⃣ Memory Trick
Memento = Memory Snapshot
🎯 12️⃣ Perfect Interview Answer
Memento is a behavioral design pattern used to capture and restore an object's state without exposing its internal structure. It is mainly used to implement undo/redo functionality.
🚀 13️⃣ Real-world Mapping
📝 Text Editor
Originator → Document  
Memento → Text snapshot  
Caretaker → Undo stack
🎮 Game
Originator → Game state  
Memento → Save file  
Caretaker → Save slots
🔥 Final Understanding
Before:
Object → State lost ❌

After:
Object → Snapshot → Restore anytime ✅